WEBVTT

00:02.579 --> 00:13.053
and I probably made a mistake and recorded on top of 
the A side of tape number one, part of what Fred has

00:02.579 --> 00:13.053
been sharing. We're now, and he is sharing with us 
his experiences with the Student Judicial Board.

00:24.709 --> 00:25.410
FRED PODESTA. Or the Judicial Board, the J Board, 
as it was called. DAVID BURRAGE. The J Board. that

00:28.887 --> 00:36.556
they charged him with failure to- No, I was taken 
before the J Board, which by the way was all

00:28.887 --> 00:36.556
appointed by me. I was taken before the J Board for 
failure to implement legislation which had been

00:36.576 --> 00:45.105
enacted by the previous student senate. And that 
was a requirement that the students be given an

00:45.866 --> 00:53.575
opportunity to vote confidence or no confidence 
in all the professors. And that this information

00:54.756 --> 00:57.139
be made available. to students such that when they 
registered for the spring semester that they

00:57.406 --> 01:06.840
would have this knowledge at hand. A piece of 
legislation, by the way, which I opposed as a

01:06.860 --> 01:13.771
student senator, but didn't have to vote because I 
was speaker. In any event,

01:15.374 --> 01:24.848
the guy who was responsible for putting this 
legislation together, who'd been the vice

01:15.374 --> 01:24.848
president for academic affairs, got angry with me 
because I didn't do it. And so he filed charges

01:28.377 --> 01:35.864
against me before the Judicial Board, which, as I 
said, I appointed all the members. And

01:37.206 --> 01:40.970
ironically, I got off on a technicality. And the 
technicality was that ultimately the charges

01:41.770 --> 01:53.923
were moved because since it had to be done in 
December and he didn't take me to the J Board until

01:41.770 --> 01:53.923
February, It was too late, so it couldn't be 
enforced anyway. But it was kind of fun there for

01:57.518 --> 02:06.589
two or three weeks, being the center of attention 
in terms of legislation that I refused to

01:57.518 --> 02:06.589
implement as student body president. Some of the 
other things that we were engaged in during that

02:06.609 --> 02:12.737
time frame, I had a couple of unpopular things that 
I was involved in. We had a fairly unsuccessful

02:12.797 --> 02:23.590
program where student government had been trying 
to help decrease the cost of textbooks for

02:24.599 --> 02:27.202
students. And we ran a thing called, it was 
actually a co-op kind of a deal, but we ran a thing

02:28.364 --> 02:34.332
called Bookmark. And we ran into one of the 
traditional problems associated with

02:36.074 --> 02:44.565
student-run volunteer organizations. couldn't 
pay anything to anybody, and so it was kind of hard

02:44.984 --> 02:48.008
to run the thing. And so we finally reached the 
conclusion that it was something that needed to be

02:48.028 --> 02:52.374
shut down. So I got the chance to shut down 
Bookmark. We also rented refrigerators, which is

02:56.419 --> 03:14.923
an interesting concept because the 
refrigerators, and again, another thing that

02:56.419 --> 03:14.923
required manpower, refrigerators were rented by 
kids who lived in the dorm, which got to the whole

02:56.419 --> 03:14.923
question of whether or not kids could have alcohol 
in dorms and what rules we were able to deal with in

03:15.325 --> 03:22.717
terms of what the use of alcohol on university 
property. And fortunately, we worked very well

03:23.679 --> 03:32.895
with the folks over at the university officials on 
the rules and regulations committee to come up

03:23.679 --> 03:32.895
with a program of work in that regard. We also, back 
early during that time frame, and this is really

03:33.636 --> 03:40.928
neat since we're about to have a dedication of this 
soon on campus, and I had the opportunity 20 years

03:41.515 --> 03:45.178
later to both piece of legislation to create a 
daycare center. The nature of the student

03:46.620 --> 03:48.882
population was changing. And back during the time 
that I was student body president, we pursued

03:49.422 --> 04:05.037
rather strongly the idea of trying to create a 
daycare facility on campus for married kids who

03:49.422 --> 04:05.037
both parents were going to school, but they didn't 
have any daycare facilities. And I'm quite proud

04:05.117 --> 04:11.083
that we're at that point now, 20 years later, at the 
university. We toured around with creating a food

04:11.823 --> 04:21.272
co-op, another opportunity to try to

04:11.823 --> 04:21.272
save kids money. But we kept running into this, how 
do you fund it kind of a scenario. But I think they

04:29.000 --> 04:30.181
were great ideas. During that time frame, too, we 
got very involved in external affairs in terms of

04:30.221 --> 04:40.952
involvement in the governance of the city of 
College Station. which we thought was important.

04:45.676 --> 04:57.827
Because since we had such a large number of 
students living there, and many of them were

04:45.676 --> 04:57.827
living off campus, that their lives were affected 
by decisions that were made by the city council. So

04:58.168 --> 05:01.751
we had regular representation there in terms of 
their meetings. And we very often got in the mix to

05:01.811 --> 05:07.456
some of the stuff that they were discussing. Two, 
we had a lot of involvement in Austin. in terms of

05:11.915 --> 05:17.262
what the Texas legislature was doing during that 
period of time. One of the big fights that we always

05:17.282 --> 05:25.111
had, which is of course one that continues 
probably even to this day, is how we divided up

05:17.282 --> 05:25.111
student service fees. It was the annual ritual 
that we went through, not unlike the federal

05:25.131 --> 05:30.017
budget process. And going through the process of 
how much money the athletic department got and how

05:30.738 --> 05:40.470
much went to the various other activities 
associated with running student-related

05:30.738 --> 05:40.470
activities on campus. And it's now about 10 or 11 
till. I don't know whether they're here yet, so we

