R.C. Potts out of the equation because of what he

08:43.626 --> 08:48.451
did. And then I've mentioned both of these other 
three or four guys earlier, Don Levi and J.C. Gray

08:48.471 --> 09:02.987
and Herman Brown because of how they molded and 
directed me during on the academic side of the

09:03.473 --> 09:05.315
equation. But you know, those guys, too, were the 
same kinds of guys that if I had some sort of,

09:05.616 --> 09:31.827
whether it was a personal problem or whether it was 
a personal challenge or whether it was

09:05.616 --> 09:31.827
something I wanted to do student 
government-wise, I wanted to bounce it off of

09:05.616 --> 09:31.827
somebody, or whether it was some other sort of 
challenge, I could see any of those guys any time.

09:33.055 --> 09:46.996
And it was something that I'm most grateful for to 
this day, the guidance that they provided me. One

09:47.016 --> 10:00.075
of the great things about all of those people I 
mentioned, and many others too, the thing that I

09:47.016 --> 10:00.075
think makes Texas A&M unique in terms of its 
student leadership opportunities is that

10:03.177 --> 10:25.521
The folks who, the adults, if you will, who are 
responsible for providing direction were always

10:03.177 --> 10:25.521
open to

10:03.177 --> 10:25.521
allowing students to make their own choices, 
allowing students to fail, even if they fail, and

10:03.177 --> 10:25.521
allow them to try something new. In other words, 
they allowed kids to lead.

10:30.430 --> 10:32.352
Yeah, there were some opportunities. There were 
some instances when we wanted to do something that

10:32.372 --> 10:40.160
perhaps the administration did not want us to do. 
But those were not that many. I remember one in

10:45.205 --> 10:49.369
particular, which is kind of a fun story. The 
university had made a decision that it wanted to

10:49.389 --> 10:57.838
shut down, I want to say it was Milner Hall, but it 
was one of the dorms over by the By Sabisa, there was

10:59.185 --> 11:12.721
one of these on air condition, had hanging pipes, 
showers in the middle of each floor, and restrooms

10:59.185 --> 11:12.721
and showers in the middle of each floor. And it 
wanted to turn it into, I believe, a math, I think it

11:13.743 --> 11:22.453
was a math office building. It might have been 
Miller. It was one of those two over at that

11:23.474 --> 11:27.319
Hotard-Miller area. And we caught wind of it. And, 
you know, we thought we came up with these really

11:30.891 --> 11:43.248
ingenious arguments that, in fact, one of our 
guys, one of the guys who was vice president on our

11:30.891 --> 11:43.248
team, either had some buddies in there or had lived 
in there at some point in time. And we didn't like

11:43.268 --> 11:48.175
the thought of taking the dormitory, you know, 
just shortage of housing. We could always make

11:48.215 --> 11:49.456
that argument. You want to keep kids on campus and 
all these kinds of things. Plus, the kids want to

11:52.100 --> 11:53.602
live there. And these old man professors didn't 
need any more space. They had space anyway. So why

11:56.946 --> 11:58.268
are we going to do this? And we individually 
lobbied the members of the Board of Regents. And we

12:03.423 --> 12:05.506
rolled the administration. And the board voted in 
our favor. We held it off for a year. We finally

12:08.569 --> 12:23.285
lost, but it was one of those where, and I'll never 
forget the anger which was expressed to us by the

12:08.569 --> 12:23.285
administration for our having the gall to go 
around their back and go lobby members of the Board

12:08.569 --> 12:23.285
of Regents. Was Freeman or Williams president? 
Uh, it was an honor to be president, so, uh, Clyde

12:25.602 --> 12:28.446
Wilson. Clyde, okay. Clyde Wilson. Uh, and, uh, 
because this is something I think had come up

12:31.169 --> 12:42.184
through academic affairs, through, I guess, John 
Calhoun was an academic affairs guy, but the guy

12:31.169 --> 12:42.184
who led that was Scott Gregson of Garrison, Texas, 
who was vice president of finance. And old Scott

12:42.204 --> 12:45.188
said, we've got to lobby the members of the board, 
and we lobbied everybody. We've got enough votes

12:45.208 --> 12:51.136
on the board of regents to turn, to get them to turn 
down the request of administration. It was kind of

12:51.236 --> 12:52.238
cool. Well, let's see, we're... I don't encourage 
that now, by the way. Okay.

